    <p class="text_block">The Center for Language Science is an interdisciplinary group of linguists,  psycholinguists, applied linguists, speech-language pathologists, speech  scientists, and cognitive neuroscientists who share an interest in language  acquisition and bilingualism. One of our primary goals is to foster  collaborative research projects across these disciplines. Our research focuses  on language science from the perspectives of typical language development,  atypical language development, psycholinguistics, and cognitive neuroscience,  using sophisticated behavioral and neuroscience methods such as eye tracking,  acoustic analysis, and electrophysiological recording of brain activity.  <br />
The CLS is supported within Penn   State by the Children,  Youth, and Families Consortium and the Colleges of Liberal Arts and Health and  Human Development.  Individual faculty  and graduate students are funded by grants from the National Institutes of  Health and the National Science Foundation.  <br />
The CLS includes affiliated researchers around the  world.  Our many national and  international collaborations bring distinguished visitors to the Penn State  campus, and provide opportunities for our students to gain valuable research  experience at other U.S.  universities as well as in other countries.   The CLS is an affiliate of the NSF Science of Learning  Center at Gallaudet University,  opening up further opportunities for collaboration in deaf studies, translation,  and sign languages.  </p>

    <p>The advisory board of the CLS comprises four  internationally-renowned researchers representing our various disciplines.</p>
    <p>Professor Laurence Leonard, Rachel E. Stark Distinguished  Professor, Purdue   University&nbsp; (language  disorders)</p>
    <p>Professor Karen Emmorey, Director, Laboratory for Language  and Cognitive Neuroscience, San    Diego State University (cognitive neuroscience)</p>
    <p>Professor Margaret Deuchar, Director, ESRC Centre for  Research on Bilingualism, University of Wales,  Bangor  (linguistics)</p>
    <p>Professor John Trueswell, Director of the IGERT Language and  Communication Program, University   of Pennsylvania  (experimental psycholinguistics) </p>

